    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Explain the how the units of volume are found in the integral of <xref ref="thm_volume_by_cross_section">Theorem</xref>:
          if <m>A(x)</m> has units of in<m>^2</m>,
          how does <m>\int A(x)\, dx</m> have units of in<m>^3</m>?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          Recall that <q><m>dx</m></q> does not just <q>sit there;</q>
          it is multiplied by <m>A(x)</m> and represents the thickness of a small slice of the solid.
          Therefore <m>dx</m> has units of in,
          giving <m>A(x)\, dx</m> the units of in<m>^3</m>.
        </p>
      </answer>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
